[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 remains at 214. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 61 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 countries from the Southeast Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 48 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
----------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 44 050 new cases (53.2% of the global newly reported cases) and 6213 deaths (71.8% of the global newly reported deaths). Of the newly confirmed cases in the region, 60.7% were reported by the USA, followed by Brazil at 14.1%, Peru at 7.9%, and Canada at 4.3%. Recognizing the USA data are overshadowing the regional proportions, without including the reported newly confirmed cases from the USA, Brazil reported 35.9% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Peru at 20.1%, Canada at 11.1%, Mexico at 8.8%, Chile at 8.3%, and Ecuador at 6.5%.

The European region reported 27 032 new cases (32.7% of the global newly reported cases) and 2081 deaths (24.0% of the global newly reported deaths). Russia reported 39.3% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, the UK 17.8%, Turkey 7.3%, Italy 7.0%, Spain 5.1%, and Belarus 3.4%.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 5618 new cases (6.8% of the global newly reported cases) and 130 deaths (1.5% of the global newly reported deaths). Saudi Arabia reported 24.2% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Pakistan at 17.6%, Iran at 14.3%, Qatar 13.8%, and the United Arab Emirates at 10.0%.

The African region reported 1465 new cases (1.8% of the global newly reported cases) and 51 deaths (0.6% of the global newly reported deaths). South Africa reported 26.3% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Nigeria at 14.9%, Algeria at 9.6%, Ghana at 6.4%, Senegal at 6.2%, and Cote d'Ivoire at 5.9%.

The Western Pacific region reported 1041 new cases (1.3% of the global newly reported cases) and 63 deaths (0.7% of the global newly reported deaths). Singapore reported 42.9% of the newly reported cases, followed by Japan at 28.2%, the Philippines at 15.0%, and Malaysia at 10.1%.

The Southeast Asia region reported 3557 new cases (4.3% of the global newly reported cases) and 119 deaths (1.4% of the global newly reported deaths). India reported 74.3% of newly reported cases, followed by Bangladesh at 15.5% and Indonesia at 8.2%. Removing India from the denominator, Bangladesh represents 60.5% of the newly reported cases, Indonesia represents 32.0%, and the Maldives 5.6%.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 3 May 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. One sees the contribution of the ongoing epidemics in Europe and the increasing cases in the Americas region, fueled by the USA, but other countries are following suit. The curve tends to drop over the weekends and rebounds following the weekend.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: It is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkin's CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have, at times, significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the John Hopkins CSSE or Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
